<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>1 November 2013</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Letter to the Chair of the Committee from Dr Jane Martin, Local Government Ombudsman</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CLG Committee Inquiry on the work of the Local Government Ombudsman</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In previous submissions to the Committee we have shared information on how the organisation has developed over the last 12 months and I look forward to exploring those issues in December. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iven the importance of leadership to the future success of LGO, I a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m taking this opportunity to give my own reflections as Chair of the Commission for Local Administration and, since Anne Seex’s absence from November of last year, the sole Local Government Ombudsman. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Operational performance</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The new caseworking arrangemen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ts introduced in Apri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l this year as a result of the transformation p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lan have been successful in helping us to deliver a swifter service to the public. Our previous submission contained detailed information about our performance which showed that since the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">introduction of the new approach we have exceeded our time targets each month. Our performance also meets or exceeds the speed of decision making of other public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sector ombudsmen. However, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> arrangements are still new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> we will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">closely monitor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> them to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensure we sustain those levels of performance.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The public not only want to receive a decision within a short timescale but also want to know that the decisions we make are accurate and fair. Our Annual Report for 2012-13 showed that both complaints about o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur service and requests for reviews of our decisions have decreased by 38% and 19% respectively. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In particular, I am pleased that we have a much better picture to report on cases which have taken over 52 weeks to conclude</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A number of these are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">joint inve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stigations with the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman (PHSO). We recognise that we need to do better and have been working with PHSO to more closely harmonise our approach so that investigations can proceed more smoothly and swiftly. We will short</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly be publishing a new protocol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clarifies our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> approach.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most of the joint investigations are complaints about health and social care and we will continue to work with PHSO to make the current statutory arrangements work as well as possible. However, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s health services become more closely integrated with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">social care at the local government level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, Parliament may need to consider whether a new legislative approach is needed to deliver a more joined up ombudsman landscape across English public services, as is currently the case in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Public confidence in the Ombud</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sman</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Public confidence in LGO is primarily driven by the quality of the service we provide. The External Evaluation of LGO concluded that our decision making procedures meet the Ombudsman Association’s principles for fairness, openness and transparency and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that our new performance management and quality framework is appropriately robust and effective. The report of the External Evaluation, along with the data we have previously submitted on our performance, show that the public can have confidence in LGO. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e have to continue to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">earn that confidence by sustaining consistently high standards. Our newly introduced quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> framework is designed to provide that assurance.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It was clear from submissions to the Committee’s previous inquiry that public conf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">idence is also affected by perceptions of the independence and impartiality of our investigations. The publication of all of our decisions, the first public sector ombudsman </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">do so, will help the public to better understand the reasons for our decisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the evidence on which they are based. In response to recommendations made by the External Evaluation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> our policy and guidance on avoiding conflicts of interest are published on our website and we also now publish details of the number of staff who have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> previously worked for a local authority. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We now need to measure how successful we have been in increasing confidence and identify areas where we have further work to do. Our business plan identifies two clear actions that will help us to measure this; cu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stomer satisfaction research and the establishment of an advisory forum. As set out in our previous submission, both of these are progressing well and by the end of the business year we will have clear data to establish how confident service users are in o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ur work. We will share those results with the Committee and on our website once they are available.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Relationship with staff</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The 2012 staff survey highlighted a number of issues for the leadership and management of the LGO to address.  In support of the cha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nges we have made I have clarified my role as Ombudsman to ensure clear leadership on casework and promote an open and accountable culture. I am accountable for my performance against objectives through a 360 degree appraisal process led by the independent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> chair of our remuneration committee </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Greater staff involvement has also been encouraged and earlier this year we established a Casework Policy Forum which I chair</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to provide a vehicle through which decisions about our policy on casework related issues ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e determined.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">My role in approving every report that we publish also ensures that I have a clear view of the significant issues arising in our casework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and give clear direction to investigators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Improving feedback channels and communication with our staf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f has also been central to a more open and accountable culture. Staff have told us that they most value face to face communication from their direct line managers. Earlier this year we introduced a new method of feeding back from our Leadership Group meeti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ngs that better meets those communications preferences of staff. A ‘Talking Points’ briefing note is produced immediately following the Leadership Group which is then discussed in all team meetings the following week. This approach ensures that everyone re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ceives contemporaneous information face to face with an opportunity to discuss and feedback to their manager.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">successfully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">managed the most significant organisational change in LGO’s forty year history.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Undoubtedly, this has been a very unsettling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> time for many people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the organisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We recognise that it is our capable and committed workforce that will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> LGO to continue to deliver an effective service and we will continue to support them as the organisation develops. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The future</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through stronger </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">leadership and a dedicated work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">force we have transformed the LGO into a more effective, cost efficient and responsive ombudsman scheme. The changes we have made place us in a strong position to meet the challenges of a rapidly changing pub</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lic services landscape.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We must now ensure that the organisation is resilient in order to meet future challenges. We have had some difficulty recruiting to posts required in the transformation plan and must ensure we have sufficient investigative capacity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to meet future </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">business </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">needs. This will be a key consideration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the rationalisation of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">future office accommodation. We also need to be able to maximise public awareness of our service especially in relation to social care.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our business plan for 2014-15 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will focus on</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the public: rolling out and monitoring our new quality standards so that we continue to provide a high quality service; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public services: better sharing the lessons from our casework with bodies in our jurisdiction to help assure local accoun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tability and support sector-led improvements in the services delivered to the public;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our staff: to continue the culture change within LGO so that we are demonstrably an organisation with strong leadership and accountability where staff feel valued and are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> able to deliver their full potential.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The next business year is also likely to see a wider debate about the role that LGO and other public sector ombudsmen should play in the future. The inquiry into complaints by the Public Administration Select Committe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e (PASC), along with the review of the ombudsman landscape by Cabinet Office Minister Oliver Letwin MP, provides an opportunity to ensure that the experiences of local government complaints and the changing face of local service delivery informs the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> direction of any reforms.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The complaints system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">public services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">including route to independent redress from the ombudsma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to reflect increasingly locally delivered and accountable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> public services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he existing complaints system may no longe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">et the needs of the citizen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a consumer of public services. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At LGO, our main purpose and focus will continue to be ensuring that our operating model delivers a quality service; that we maintain a sustainable workforce and that we remain an authoritative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> voice that engenders public trust and confidence.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">1 November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:111.6pt; width:391.7pt"><tr style="height:3.7pt"><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:122.4pt"><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:120.4pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:148.9pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>